   <abstract>While we imagine modern France as a nation with a vibrant and powerful public sector, many of its most essential tasks in resource and infrastructure management, as well as services such as water, gas and electric utilities are largely provided by private entities today. This should not surprise us if we take a much longer view of French history as the early modern France state was firmly grounded in privatizing all kinds of public infrastructure and resources. The French revolutionaries set themselves the task of abolishing the principles that undergirded the Old Regime, including privatization, and imagined a new ideal of public control of France's infrastructure, taxes, and other kinds of public powers like justice. But this process was halted by the fiscal realities of the fledgling French republic. Instead of persevering with public administration of the nation's greatest assets, the revolutionaries slowly reinstituted privatization as the dominant mode of administering France's public services and properties. By challenging more typical narratives of the French Revolution as a break with the Old Regime past, this dissertation argues that it was more of a realignment and reimagining of Old Regime legal and financial tools for revolutionary purposes. It further argues that the familiar modern dichotomy between, privatization and public control, is a product of the French Revolution. The debates in revolutionary France over infrastructure and taxes crystallized new ways of thinking about the role of the modern state and its responsibilities to the public, the limits of that state, and framed powerful arguments about the desirability of privatization over public control. Arguments that continue to dominate contemporary global debates over privatization and the ever-expanding control of public property by international corporations.</abstract>
